---
scope: .github/ + README.md
description: GitHub repository presence — the README signpost and header banner that redirect visitors to the MCP server repo.
intent: >
  When someone lands on the aidemd.dev GitHub repository, the README tells them
  in one sentence what AIDE is, sends them to the server repo where the
  installable tool and contributions live, and makes clear this repo is the
  website source maintained by the core team. A header banner anchors the page
  visually using the site's achromatic design language, switching between dark
  and light variants to match the viewer's GitHub theme. The entire README is a
  signpost — 100 to 200 words that answer "where do I go?" and nothing else.
outcomes:
  desired:
    - A visitor who opens the repository page on GitHub can identify within five seconds that this is the website source, not the tool, and sees a prominent link to the server repo.
    - The README contains no setup instructions, no tech stack listing, no methodology explanation beyond one sentence, and no contribution invitation — those belong in the server repo.
    - The header banner renders correctly on GitHub in both dark and light modes via the picture element, with no visible breakage, no fallback-to-alt-text, and no aspect ratio distortion.
    - The banner's visual language matches the site's design tokens — Inter font, zinc palette, achromatic — so a visitor who clicks through to aidemd.dev perceives continuity, not a brand mismatch.
  undesired:
    - A README that tries to sell AIDE, explain the methodology, or document the pipeline — turning the signpost into a landing page and duplicating content that belongs on aidemd.dev or in the server repo's README.
    - A banner that introduces color, gradients, illustrations, or visual elements outside the site's achromatic design language — creating a first impression that the site itself will then contradict.
    - A banner that only works in one GitHub theme (dark or light) because the picture element is missing or misconfigured, causing viewers in the other theme to see a clashing or invisible image.
---

## Context

This repo hosts the aidemd.dev website — not the AIDE tool. Visitors arrive
here one of two ways: clicking "Source" from the live site, or finding the
repo through GitHub search while looking for AIDE itself. In both cases the
visitor's actual intent is almost never "read the website source code." It is
either "install AIDE" or "contribute to AIDE," and both of those happen in
the server repo. The README's only job is to confirm what this repo is,
redirect the visitor to where they actually want to be, and do so before
they close the tab.

The header banner is the first visual a visitor sees on the GitHub repo page.
GitHub renders README images inside a constrained column (830px max on
desktop) and offers both dark and light themes that users can toggle
independently of their OS setting. A banner that only works in one theme
looks broken to roughly half the audience. The banner must also read as
continuous with the aidemd.dev site itself — if the GitHub page introduces
color or illustration the site doesn't use, the visitor's first impression
contradicts the site they click through to.

## Strategy

**The README is a signpost, not a door.** Across twelve real website-repo
READMEs, the highest-rated pattern (modelcontextprotocol/docs, 5/5) is a
minimal redirect: one sentence identifying the repo, one bold link to the
canonical location, one sentence on where to file issues. The lowest-rated
(biomejs/website, prisma/docs, both 2/5) are pure developer-setup READMEs
with no orientation — they assume every visitor already knows what they are
looking at. The README uses the minimal-redirect pattern because its intent
is redirection, not contribution onboarding.

**Scope declaration goes in the first sentence.** The tailwindlabs/tailwindcss.com
and commonmark/commonmark-spec READMEs both lead with "what this is and is
not" framing in sentence one, never burying the distinction below setup
instructions. The README opens with a single sentence naming this repo as
the website source, then immediately names the server repo as the place
visitors actually want.

**Word count stays between 100 and 200.** Research across twelve repos shows
that non-contributable website READMEs land in a sweet spot: shorter than
100 words risks missing the redirect entirely, longer than 200 words buries
it. The README targets this range and does not exceed it.

**No contribution invitation, no dev setup, no tech stack.** The
tailwindlabs/tailwindcss.com README explicitly states "not licensed under
an open-source license" and accepts fixes for minor mistakes only. For a
non-contributable repo, including contribution instructions creates
confusion and generates unwanted PRs. The README states that the site is
maintained by the core team and directs all contribution energy to the
server repo.

**One sentence on AIDE, maximum.** The commonmark/commonmark-spec and
tc39/proposal-temporal READMEs show the right proportion: one line on what
the spec/methodology does, then immediately redirect to implementations.
The README gives one sentence defining AIDE's purpose (for visitors who
arrived without context), then redirects. No methodology explanation, no
pipeline diagram, no feature list — those live on aidemd.dev and in the
server repo.

**Banner uses SVG with the HTML picture element for dual-mode switching.**
GitHub officially supports the `<picture>` element with
`prefers-color-scheme` media queries, and this maps to GitHub's own theme
toggle (not just OS-level dark mode). The deprecated fragment-identifier
method (`#gh-dark-mode-only`) still works but is not recommended for new
work. Embedded SVG media queries fail in Safari entirely. The picture
element is the only method that works reliably across all browsers and
GitHub's theme system. Tailwind CSS's README is the reference
implementation.

**Banner is a wordmark with short tagline, not a logo-only mark.** AIDE is
not yet a household name — the acronym alone is opaque to a first-time
visitor. A wordmark-plus-tagline banner (e.g., "AIDE" in Inter bold with
"Autonomous Intent-Driven Engineering" or a compressed variant below)
provides immediate recognition context. Once brand recognition is
established, a logo-only approach becomes viable. The tagline is rendered
as SVG text so it remains editable without regenerating raster assets.

**Banner dimensions target wordmark proportions, not full-width cinematic.**
Research shows two viable dimension classes: logo-only at 350-400 x 70-80px
(5:1 ratio, per Tailwind CSS) and full-width at 830 x 200-300px (3:1-4:1
ratio, per Astro). A wordmark-plus-tagline fits the wider format — target
approximately 830 x 120px rendered, with source at 2x for retina. GitHub
applies `max-width: 100%` automatically, so the banner scales down on
mobile without special handling.

**Two SVG files stored in .github/, transparent backgrounds.** Dark variant:
light text on transparent background (blends with GitHub dark theme). Light
variant: dark text on transparent background (blends with GitHub light
theme). Both use the site's design tokens — Inter font, zinc palette
(zinc-100 for light text, zinc-950 for dark text). Files live in `.github/`
alongside the spec, version-controlled. No external CDN hosting — Prisma's
use of Imgur for banner hosting is an anti-pattern that creates a fragile
external dependency.

**Banner is centered on the page.** GitHub supports `align="center"` on
wrapper elements. Most polished repos (Tailwind CSS, Astro) center their
banners. A left-aligned banner reads as less considered. The banner is
wrapped in a centered container.

**Alt text is meaningful.** The banner's `<img>` fallback includes alt text
that communicates the project name and purpose ("AIDE — Autonomous
Intent-Driven Engineering") rather than a generic "banner" or "logo"
label. This serves accessibility and provides context if image loading
fails.

## Good examples

The GitHub repo page loads. A centered banner reads "AIDE" in a clean
sans-serif with "Autonomous Intent-Driven Engineering" set smaller beneath
it, rendered in near-white on GitHub's dark theme or near-black on its
light theme, blending seamlessly with the page background. Below the banner:

> **This repo contains the source for [aidemd.dev](https://aidemd.dev), the
> website for the AIDE methodology.**
>
> AIDE cascades your intent through specialized agents into working code.
>
> **Looking for the tool?** Install and contribute at
> [aidemd-mcp/server](https://github.com/aidemd-mcp/server).
>
> This site is maintained by the core team. For bugs, features, and
> contributions, see the server repo above.

Total: roughly 60 words of body text plus the banner. A visitor who opened
the page looking for the installable tool finds the server repo link within
three seconds and clicks through. A visitor who was curious about the
website source gets confirmation in one sentence and knows not to open PRs
here. Switching GitHub from dark to light theme shows the banner swap
cleanly — no flash of wrong-colored text, no hard-edged rectangle, no
fallback to alt text.

## Bad examples

The README opens with a full-width JPG banner showing a gradient wash in
blue and purple with the text "Build the future with AIDE" — colors and
language that appear nowhere on aidemd.dev. Below it, two hundred words
explain the eight-agent pipeline, what cascading intent means, why AIDE
beats rules packs, and how the brain stores domain knowledge — all content
that duplicates the landing page and the server repo's README. A "Getting
Started" section follows with `pnpm install && pnpm dev` instructions,
inviting drive-by contributors to a repo that does not accept outside
contributions. The server repo link appears at the bottom, below the fold,
after content the visitor was never looking for. On GitHub's light theme,
the dark JPG banner creates a harsh rectangular block because JPG does not
support transparency and no picture element was used. There is no alt text
on the image. The README is 600 words long and answers every question except
the one the visitor actually had: "Where is the tool?"

Another failure mode: the README is a single line — "aidemd.dev" — with no
banner, no link to the server repo, and no indication of what AIDE is. A
visitor who arrives via GitHub search has zero context and no path forward.
This is the biomejs/website anti-pattern: assuming every visitor already
knows what they are looking at.

## References

- `research/open-source-readme/website-repo-readme-patterns` -- Minimal-redirect pattern rated 5/5 (modelcontextprotocol/docs) and the 100-200 word sweet spot for non-contributable website repos; anti-patterns for pure dev-setup READMEs (biomejs, prisma rated 2/5); scope-declaration-first pattern from tailwindcss.com and commonmark-spec.
- `research/open-source-readme/website-repo-readme-examples` -- The modelcontextprotocol/docs 3-line redirect as the closest model; tailwindcss.com's explicit "not open-source licensed" contribution framing; tc39/proposal-temporal's spec-vs-implementation separation pattern.
- `research/github-readme-banners/github-rendering-technical` -- GitHub desktop container width of 830px; picture element as the current standard for dark/light switching (deprecated fragment identifiers confirmed); SVG embedded media queries fail in Safari; max-width 100% automatic responsive behavior; centering via align center wrapper.
- `research/github-readme-banners/github-readme-banner-design-patterns` -- Tailwind CSS reference implementation (SVG, 350x70, picture element, dual variants); wordmark-plus-tagline recommendation for repos without established brand recognition; AIDE design token extraction (Inter, zinc palette, achromatic); in-repo .github/ hosting over external CDN.
